Other Consumption per Capita=A FUNCTION OF(Other Consumption per Capita) ~~|
Other Consumption per Capita=
	~	EUR
	~		|

Other Consumption Per Household  = A FUNCTION OF( Mean Household Size,Other Consumption per Capita\
		) ~~|
Other Consumption Per Household=
	Other Consumption per Capita * Mean Household Size
	~	EUR
	~		|

Agricultural Rent  = A FUNCTION OF( )
	~	
	~		|

Land per Household  = A FUNCTION OF( Land per Capita,Mean Household Size) ~~|
Land per Household=
	Land per Capita * Mean Household Size
	~	
	~		|

Mean Household Income=
	Income per Capita * Mean Household Size
	~	EUR
	~		|

Economic Land Conversion Demand  = A FUNCTION OF( Transition Inertia,-Urban Land) ~~|
Economic Land Conversion Demand=MAX ( 0  , (Desired Urban Land Total  - Urban Land) )
	~	
	~		|

Transport Cost per km=A FUNCTION OF(Transport Cost per km) ~~|
Transport Cost per km=
	~	EUR/km
	~	"Imagine a circular city in a featureless plain. All employment is in a central
		business district (CBD), which we take to be a point at the city’s center. The city
		is populated by N identical individuals. Each individual makes one round trip
		per day to the CBD, where he works a fixed number of hours and receives a daily
		wage of y. The greater the radial distance from the center at which an individual
		resides, the greater is the cost of this commute. Specifically, for an individual
		who lives at radial distance x, daily commuting cost is assumed to be tx, where
		t > 0 is a constant round-trip commuting cost per unit distance. The cost of
		commuting will be treated as an out-of-pocket cost, rather than a time \
		cost." (Marvin Kraus, \
		https://matthewturner.org/ec1410/readings/Krause_bc_2000.pdf)
	|

Urban Fringe Radius=
	MAX(0, (Mean Household Income - Other Consumption Per Household - Land per Household\
		 * Agricultural Rent) / Transport Cost per km)
	~	km
	~	x_star = (Y - z - q * R_A) / t Bedeutung:
		
		Ursp. Budgetfunktion (auf Hashaltsbasis): Y = z + R(x) * q + t * x
		Y = Haushaltseinkommen
		z = sonstiger Konsum
		R(x) = urbane Bodenrente bei Distanz x
		q = Landkonsum pro Haushalt
		t = Transportkosten pro km
		x = Distanz zum Zentrum
		
		Nach R(x) umgestellt:
		
		R(x) = (Y - z - t * x) / q
		
		An der Stadtgrenze x_star gilt die AMM-Gleichgewichtsbedingung:
		
		R(x_star) = R_A
		
		mit R_A = Agrarland-Rente.
		
		Einsetzen:
		
		R_A = (Y - z - t * x_star) / q
		
		Nach x_star umgestellt:
		
		x_star = (Y - z - q * R_A) / t
		
		Diese Variable verwendet x_star als Urban Fringe Radius.
	|

